<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  FastDDS reader QoS override for /tf.

  Why: Create3 publishes /tf with RELIABLE QoS. A RELIABLE writer keeps
  per-matched-reader history to track unacked samples. Each time we kill
  and relaunch SLAM/Nav2/RViz, the old readers leave phantom proxies on
  Create3's writer side until DDS liveliness/lease timeout reaps them
  (10s+). Cycling launches faster than that piles up phantoms, exhausts
  the writer's resource_limits, and Create3's /tf writer enters a
  permanently stalled state — recoverable only by physically rebooting
  the robot.

  DDS QoS rule: a reader's reliability may be <= the writer's. Declaring
  /tf readers as BEST_EFFORT still matches Create3's RELIABLE writer, but
  the writer no longer tracks unacked samples for them — eliminating the
  resource exhaustion path entirely.

  Mechanism: rmw_fastrtps looks up a per-topic data_reader profile by the
  ROS-prefixed topic name (`rt/<topic>`) when creating a subscriber. We
  do NOT override /tf_static because it relies on TRANSIENT_LOCAL +
  RELIABLE for late-joiner delivery and is low-rate (no churn risk).

  Wire-in: scripts/setup_robot.sh and scripts/setup_workstation.sh both
  export FASTRTPS_DEFAULT_PROFILES_FILE pointing at this file. The
  participant profile is left to be generated from the existing
  ROS_DISCOVERY_SERVER / ROS_SUPER_CLIENT env vars — this XML only
  contributes the data_reader profile, so the discovery topology is
  unchanged.
-->
<profiles xmlns="http://www.eprosima.com/XMLSchemas/fastRTPS_Profiles">

    <data_reader profile_name="rt/tf">
        <qos>
            <reliability>
                <kind>BEST_EFFORT</kind>
            </reliability>
        </qos>
    </data_reader>

</profiles>
